        "title": 		"USB Encryption/Digital Password Book",
        "body": <<<"
			<p>Storing passwords on a USB drive with encryption or using a digital password book can provide a portable and secure solution for password management. With encryption, passwords are protected by a secure key, ensuring that even if the USB drive is lost or stolen, the data remains inaccessible to unauthorised individuals. Digital password books offer similar functionality, allowing users to store passwords securely on their devices, often with additional features such as password generation and autofill. However, it's crucial to keep the USB drive or device containing the digital password book in a safe and secure location to prevent unauthorised access. It’s important to also have a backup and regularly update it - think about how you’ll manage this before deciding on this technique.</p>
		">>>,
        "instruction": "",

		"_items": [
			{
				"title": "Tips for using this password storage technique",
				"body": <<<"
					<p><strong>Use User-Friendly Encryption Tools:</strong> Use tools like <w.hyperlink href="https://www.veracrypt.fr/code/VeraCrypt/">VeraCrypt</w.hyperlink> or <w.hyperlink href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/operating-system-security/data-protection/bitlocker/">BitLocker</w.hyperlink> or <w.hyperlink href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-au/microsoft-365/previous-versions/office-2010">Microsoft Office 10</w.hyperlink> (evaluate and use these tools at your discretion, they are suggestions only), which offer straightforward interfaces to encrypt your USB drive. Follow step-by-step guides or video tutorials available online.</p>

					<p><strong>Choose Devices with Built-in Encryption:</strong> Purchase USB drives with built-in encryption, like the Kingston DataTraveler Vault Privacy, which simplifies the encryption process.</p>

					<p><strong>Back Up Your Primary USB on a Secondary or Multiple Drives:</strong> Make copies of your files or digital password book and back it up on a secondary USB or external hard drive. Ensure that you encrypt the backup drive and back it up regularly, especially once you have added new passwords.</p>
				">>>
			}
		]
